OpenDKIM is a Linux mail server service used to add and verify DKIM signatures on emails.

In simple terms:

When your mail server sends an email, OpenDKIM adds a digital signature to the message.
Receiving mail servers check that signature using your domain’s DNS records.
This proves:
the email really came from your domain
the message was not modified during delivery

It helps prevent:

email spoofing
phishing
spam impersonating your domain

Commonly used with:

Postfix
Sendmail
Exim

Basic flow:

Your server sends mail
OpenDKIM signs it with a private key
Public key is stored in DNS
Receiver verifies the signature

Without DKIM:

emails may go to spam
attackers can fake your domain more easily

So, OpenDKIM is mainly for email authentication and trust on Linux mail servers.
